    {
      "id": "RQ-0046",
      "status": "todo",
      "title": "Make push_upstream_with_rebase fail or recover when a no-upstream branch is behind remote",
      "description": "Principles violated: F (fail fast appropriately), J (consistency/integrity), H (operational hygiene). `push_upstream_with_rebase()` can return success for a branch with no upstream even when the local branch is already behind `origin/<branch>`, because the early no-upstream path only checks whether HEAD is ahead of the fallback ref and returns `Ok(())` when it is not. Why it matters: worker finalization and other publish paths can silently leave a branch behind remote while reporting success, which defeats the whole purpose of the rebase-aware push helper in concurrent update scenarios. Minimal fix: when no upstream is configured, treat behind-or-diverged `origin/<branch>` state as work to repair with fetch/rebase/upstream setup rather than as a successful no-op. Acceptance criteria: a regression reproduces the behind-without-upstream scenario and proves the helper either rebases/pushes to a synced state or returns an explicit error, and the git commit helper tests pass.",
      "priority": "high",
      "tags": [
        "maintenance",
        "git",
        "parallel"
      ],
      "scope": [
        "crates/ralph/src/git/commit/rebase_push.rs",
        "crates/ralph/src/git/commit/tests.rs",
        "cargo test -p ralph-agent-loop git"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "path: crates/ralph/src/git/commit/rebase_push.rs:42-60 :: the no-upstream path computes ahead against fallback_upstream and returns Ok(()) when HEAD is not ahead, even before checking whether the branch is behind remote",
        "workflow: temp path harness calling ralph::git::push_upstream_with_rebase on a no-upstream branch after `git fetch origin ralph/RQ-0940` :: observed RESULT=Ok(()) while `git status --short --branch` still reported `## ralph/RQ-0940...origin/ralph/RQ-0940 [behind 1]`",
        "path: crates/ralph/src/git/commit/tests.rs:25-90 :: current coverage exercises non-fast-forward recovery and remote-existing upstream setup, but not the behind-without-upstream case"
      ],
      "plan": [
        "Update the no-upstream branch path to distinguish clean synced state from behind-or-diverged fallback-upstream state before returning success.",
        "Repair behind state by fetching, rebasing, and setting upstream when appropriate, or return an explicit error if automatic recovery is unsafe.",
        "Add a regression that reproduces the fetched-behind no-upstream scenario and asserts the helper does not report success while still behind remote.",
        "Verify by running the git helper regression and the broader git commit helper tests, then confirm the reproduced temp harness no longer returns `Ok(())` while behind."
      ],
      "notes": [],
      "request": "scan: parallel run bookkeeping, worker workspace sync, git push/rebase races, and webhook delivery retries/redaction",
